\b Interpretation and discussion (Part 1)\b0\par
The recorded waveforms indicate that probe selection strongly impacts the apparent ringing, overshoot, and even the perceived edge speed. In particular, single-ended probing can introduce additional loop inductance through the ground connection, which can resonate with probe capacitance and present as pronounced oscillations after the transition. Differential probing reduces ground-reference related errors and is generally better suited for high dV/dt nodes.\par
\par
Low-impedance (low-Z) probing changes the loading of the measured node. While this can suppress certain oscillations, it may also modify the circuit behavior and can reduce the allowable measurable voltage range. Consequently, the measured waveform must be interpreted as a combination of the actual node behavior and the measurement chain transfer characteristics.\par
\par
Finally, bandwidth constraints of the probe and oscilloscope limit the ability to resolve steep edges. Insufficient bandwidth typically leads to underestimated peak values and artificially increased rise/fall times. These limitations are considered when comparing the extracted parameters between probe configurations.\par
\par

\b 2.4.2 Measurement Evaluation for Part 2 (gate charge determination)\b0\par
\b Method summary\b0\par
Gate charge is obtained from the measured gate-resistor voltage by converting the voltage drop to gate current using Rg = 3.3 ohm and integrating the resulting current over the transition interval. The evaluation is repeated for 15 V, 20 V, and 30 V operation and for both EPC2202 and GS61008T in high-side and low-side operation.\par
